<br>
&quot;So long as the person casting on you STARTS casting the spell AFTER you are FD and you remain FD until the spell finishes then the caster will not be placed on the hate list of any mobs the monk is hated by. If they start casting and then you FD or you get up before the spell finishes then the caster gets agro as well&quot;<br>
<br>
this is wrong. no caster will get agro on starting a spell. casters will agro only on spell impect. of course a succesful FD before the impact will avoid agro on the caster.<br>
<br>
two more hints that comes into my mind....<br>
<br>
a running mob will not give his hate list to other mobs. so a monk can finish a mob, that runs into a crowd of other mobs and FD then without the rest of the group getting agro.<br>
<br>
another way to split velious mobs is to pull the mobs near another mob. when you FD and the mobs start to walk back, one caster will buff the nearby mob with some luck and get behind the others.<br>
<br>
Minng Buda <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukahlimaa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kahlimaa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(7/30/02 8:55:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=291.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Laotzu's Guide to Advanced Pulling</span><hr size=1> First of all, someone mentioned something about snare/root items.  In the Warrens (on Odus) if you kill the Prince (a lvl 15 or so mob) he will almost always drop a 'tiny bag of dice' (he's on a 30min timer).  You take these no drop/lore dice to Miranda (she's one of the 'kittens' under the tree) in the kitty town in Stonebrunt Mountains.  She will give you in return a 4 charge snare item, a 'ball of yarn' I believe.  The ball of yarn is no drop, but not lore, so you can do this as many times as you like.  It's a very simple quest and the only hard part is running through Stonebrunt, which is very easy for a monk using FD when needed.  <br>
As for pulling, my main for a very long time was a warrior, and warriors have very limited options when it comes to pulling.  Over time I became and expert in 'aggro-radius pulling'.  It's a very simple technique but requires you to know a lot about the mobs you are pulling.  What thier pathing is when pulled, exactly how close to them you have to be to get aggro, whether it is safe to pull them with ranged weaps or not (some mobs seem to have a larger aggro radius when you use a ranged weapon to pull, and will bring all thier friends), etc.  And although I have a hard time explaining how to do it to others, it works extremely well.  I have had people mention to me how amazing it was that I could single pull in certain places apparently using nothing (spells, special abilities) to do it.  This has been incredibly useful when playing my monk.  Not only can I aggro pull, but if I do make a mistake, or am trying to learn the lay of a zone I don't have experience in, I can always FD and get myself out of a bad situation.  The only way I can explain to someone how to learn this technique is (for a monk) forget you have FD.  Pretend that if you pull too many you will surely die.  Instead of running up to mobs and whacking them, slowly approach them and let them aggro you first, watch and see how close you have to be to get them to aggro you and how far from each other they have to be not to bring others, and learn the pathing of each mob, how they will run to you, and how they will return to thier bind point.  Good luck all, and happy hunting.<br>
